{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9a53737f-7868-4c06-b304-8fa7a59ec71f","content":"**Starting with MSTest.Sdk 4.0.0, the VSTest compatibility layer is disabled by default.**\n\nMSTest 4.x uses **Microsoft.Testing.Platform** as the sole runner. The legacy VSTest adapter (`Microsoft.VisualStudio.TestPlatform`) is no longer included, which is why `vstest.console` can't discover your tests.\n\n### Your options\n\n1. **Migrate your CI to `dotnet test`** (recommended) — it works with Microsoft.Testing.Platform natively:\n   ```\n   dotnet test TestProject.csproj\n   ```\n\n2. **Re-enable the VSTest bridge** if you must keep `vstest.console`, by adding this to your `.csproj`:\n   ```xml\n   <EnableMicrosoftTestingExtensionsCodeCoverage>true</EnableMicrosoftTestingExtensionsCodeCoverage>\n   ```\n   or more directly:\n   ```xml\n   <TestingExtensionsProfile>Default</TestingExtensionsProfile>\n   ```\n   which opts back into the VSTest compatibility adapter.\n\n3. **Pin to 3.x** until your pipeline can be updated:\n   ```xml\n   <Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n   ```\n\nOption 1 (`dotnet test`) is the path forward — it's what MSTest 4.x is designed around. Would you like me to update your project or CI pipeline?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d794eecc-faeb-4af8-8db5-ec45982e6050","outputTokens":340},"id":"fac4c348-8069-44d3-9242-1b50662bf400","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:35:09.040Z","parentId":"4ea32f63-0997-4dc4-ace5-38993ca514d5"}
